<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="131" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1217,1530]" pageId="3" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1217,1242]" pageId="3" pageNumber="131">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Small or medium-sized moths with different wing coloration and pattern. Male antennae are fasciculate, female antennae are filiform. In the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[734,870,1253,1278]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 9–11" captionStart-1="FIGURES 12–13" captionStartId-0="4.[151,264,1953,1975]" captionStartId-1="6.[151,264,1871,1893]" captionTargetBox-0="[189,1424,217,1931]" captionTargetBox-1="[178,1408,636,1843]" captionTargetId-0="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1932]" captionTargetId-1="figure@6.[151,1436,628,1850]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionText-0="FIGURES 9–11. Lithosiini spp.: male genitalia. 9, Planovalvata confusa, holotype, China, Guangdong, slide AV2451m Volynkin; 10, P. confusa, paratype, N Vietnam, slide MWM 31389 Volynkin; 11, Stigmatophora (Stigmatophora) roseivena, Myanmar, slide MWM 31392 Volynkin." captionText-1="FIGURES 12–13. Stigmatophora spp.: male genitalia. 12, Stigmatophora (Stigmatophora) micans, the type speCies of Stigmatophora, Russian Far East, Khabarovsk terr., slide AV3079 Volynkin; 13, Stigmatophora (Pseudomiltochrista) zolotuhini, NE India, Assam, slide MWM 31393 Volynkin." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1196986/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1196988/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="131">Figs. 11–12</figureCitation>
), like in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Börner" authorityYear="1932" box="[1036,1149,1253,1278]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Endrosina">Endrosina</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation box="[1157,1304,1254,1278]" pageId="3" pageNumber="131" refId="ref4793" refString="Borner, C. (1920) Ord. Lepidoptera, SChmetterlinge. In: Brohmer, P. (Ed.), Fauna von Deutschland (ein Beschtimmungsbuch unserer heimischen Tierwelt), 2, verbesserte Auflage. Quelle &amp; Meyer, Leipzig, pp. 328 - 355." type="journal article">Börner, 1920</bibRefCitation>
genera, the valve with well developed thorn-like harpe medio-subbasally; the costa is weakly sclerotized, without medial and distal processes; the sacculus with a well developed distal process; the vesica consists of one dorsal subbasal membranous diverticulum and large sack-like distal section with fields of spine- or tooth-like scobination and/or clusters of numerous small but robust cornuti. The female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[946,1083,1397,1422]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1922,1944]" captionTargetBox="[156,1428,1084,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,1078,1900]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 14–16. Stigmatophora spp.: female genitalia. 14, Stigmatophora (Stigmatophora) roseivena, N Vietnam, slide MWM 31391 Volynkin; 15, S. (S.) micans, the type speCies of Stigmatophora, Russian Far East, Khabarovsk terr., slide AV3080 Volynkin; 16, S. (P.) zolotuhini, NE India, Assam, slide MWM 31394 Volynkin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1196990/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="131">Figs. 14–15</figureCitation>
) are characterized by the very long, well sclerotized and dorso-ventrally flattened ductus bursae, the small, elliptical corpus bursae with a strong spine-like scobination, and the very long and narrow appendix bursae directed posteriorly. Genital differences from 
<emphasis box="[151,369,1505,1529]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="131">Pseudomiltochrista</emphasis>
are described in the diagnosis of the latter.
</paragraph>
